<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1398,311,372]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[648,741,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angusta">
<emphasis box="[648,741,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">angusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ meaning ‘narrow’, and refers to the slender habitus of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
